The Unified Purification-Reversion (UPR) Defense method combines advanced trigger reversion, efficient numerical purification, and a novel dual-space consistency loss. The process begins with an advanced trigger reversion mechanism that provides an initial estimate of the backdoor trigger. Unlike TERD, which uses noise sampled directly from a prior, UPR Defense uses a controlled noisy initialization managed by a randomness control scheme inspired by Purify++, reducing variance and preventing overcorrection. Subsequently, an adaptive purification process replaces the computationally expensive differential multi-step samplers with a Heun’s method-based numerical simulation, balancing computational efficiency and reliable reverse diffusion. Following the trigger reversion, UPR Defense employs a dual-space consistency loss: in the noise space, the Kullback-Leibler divergence between the reversed trigger distribution and a benign noise distribution is minimized, while in the image space, a consistency loss ensures that the purified output closely resembles a benign image. Additionally, a controlled randomness mechanism is integrated via a mixing strategy that combines deterministic updates with injected stochastic noise, and an adaptive noise schedule adjusts noise intensity over iterations, providing further refinement when needed. All components are jointly optimized by minimizing a loss function that comprises both image-space and noise-space consistency terms and a regularization term to prevent excessive deviations during purification. 

\begin{algorithm}
\caption{UPR Defense Procedure}
\begin{algorithmic}
  \State Initialize input with controlled noisy initialization.
  \State Perform trigger reversion using adaptive purification via Heun's method.
  \State Compute the image-space consistency loss and the noise-space Kullback-Leibler divergence.
  \State Update the model parameters using a mixing strategy that combines deterministic updates with injected stochastic noise.
  \State Adjust the noise schedule adaptively over iterations until convergence is reached.
\end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}

