The evaluation of UPR Defense is conducted on datasets such as CIFAR-10 and CelebA, simulating both forward and reverse diffusion processes with synthetically added triggers of varying intensities. Three primary experiments are designed to thoroughly assess the defense mechanism.

\subsection{Robustness Evaluation}
The first experiment examines the robustness of UPR Defense under different trigger intensities. A small bright square trigger is added, scaled by factors of 0.2, 0.5, 0.8, and 1.0. UPR Defense is then compared to a baseline TERD method. Reconstruction quality is quantified using the Peak Signal-to-Noise Ratio (PSNR), Structural Similarity Index (SSIM), and detection accuracy (with a threshold set at PSNR > 30).

\subsection{Computational Efficiency and Convergence}
The second experiment assesses computational efficiency and convergence speed by comparing the traditional multi-step sampler in TERD with the Heun’s method-based sampler in UPR Defense. This involves measuring the wall-clock time per sample and counting the number of iterations required to reach a consistency loss threshold (e.g., 1e-3) over a set of 30 test images, utilizing timing functions available in Python and efficient tensor operations in PyTorch.

\subsection{Randomness and Adaptive Noise Scheduling}
The third experiment investigates the effect of controlled randomness and adaptive noise scheduling. Through grid searches over different mixing coefficients (0.1, 0.5, 0.9) and various noise schedules (constant, linear, exponential), the consistency loss is tracked over 50 iterations for each configuration. Average loss curves are computed to analyze the convergence behavior. The experiments are implemented using Python with PyTorch, NumPy, and Matplotlib, and utility functions are incorporated for adding trigger patterns, computing loss functions, and visualizing loss versus iteration curves. All experimental protocols ensure reproducibility and provide comprehensive quantitative and qualitative comparisons between UPR Defense and baseline approaches.

