\section{Results}
\label{sec:results}
Experimental results indicate that UPR Defense outperforms baseline defenses such as TERD. In the robustness experiments, UPR Defense consistently maintains high reconstruction quality across different trigger intensities, with average PSNR and SSIM values demonstrating that the purified images closely resemble their benign counterparts. Detection accuracies approach 100% when using a PSNR threshold above 30. The reconstruction quality plots validate that the dual-space consistency loss effectively reverses even low-intensity triggers without introducing significant artifacts. 

In the computational efficiency experiment, the UPR Defense variant employing Heun’s method converges more rapidly than the traditional multi-step sampler, requiring fewer iterations and lower wall-clock times per sample. Quantitative comparisons reveal that both the average time per sample and the number of iterations are significantly reduced for the UPR-Heun approach in comparison to TERD. 

Grid search experiments focusing on controlled randomness and adaptive noise scheduling further demonstrate that a mid-range mixing coefficient (approximately 0.5) paired with a linear decay noise schedule offers the best balance between robust trigger reversal and stable convergence. Although challenges remain when confronting highly adaptive attack strategies, the overall results substantiate the effectiveness and efficiency of UPR Defense in mitigating backdoor attacks on diffusion models.

\section{Conclusions and Future Work}
\label{sec:conclusion}
This work has presented Unified Purification-Reversion (UPR) Defense, a novel framework for defending diffusion models against backdoor attacks. By integrating an advanced trigger reversion strategy with efficient Heun’s method-based numerical purification and a dual consistency loss that operates across both image and noise spaces, UPR Defense addresses several key limitations of existing methods such as TERD. Experimental evaluations on datasets like CIFAR-10 and CelebA demonstrate that UPR Defense achieves superior reconstruction quality, robust trigger reversal, and significant reductions in computational overhead. The incorporation of controlled randomness via a mixing strategy and adaptive noise scheduling further enhances its resilience against both low-intensity and adaptive backdoor triggers. Although some challenges remain in fully neutralizing adaptive attack scenarios, the proposed framework represents a substantial advancement toward secure and reliable diffusion models. Future work will explore extensions to additional generative architectures and further refinements in the purification process through advanced regularization techniques.

